Restoring Backup
Restoration of a backup works when there is an empty data directory. If required, recreate the data directory before the restoration. Following command is helpful to perform the restore of a backup. 

$ pgbackrest restore --stanza=pg0app --log-level-console=info
Sample steps:

Stop the PostgreSQL instance.

$ sudo systemctl stop postgresql-11
Clean the data directory of the corrupt instance

$ rm -rf /var/lib/pgsql/11/data
Create the data directory and make sure that right permissions are there

$ mkdir /var/lib/pgsql/11/data/
$ chmod 0700 /var/lib/pgsql/11/data
Restore the backup. Restoration of backup is as simple as just executing a single command. When this command is executed, it restores the recently successful full backup and all the incremental backups and archives pushed using pgBackRest to the backup repository. 

pgbackrest restore --stanza=pg0app --log-level-console=info
Start the PostgreSQL Service

sudo systemctl start postgresql-11
So far, we have seen how the basic backup and restoration can be done with a backup taken to the filesystem using pgBackRest

Backup to Amazon S3 Bucket
Many organizations prefer to backup their database to the cloud. Using cloud storage is effectively cheaper and reliable in many cases. Here we're showcasing how easy it is to set up backup to S3.  An s3 bucket needs to be set up following the Amazon documentation. Before configuring the PostgreSQL backup, it is highly recommended to verify the access using aws cli and push a file to the bucket as shown below.

$ aws s3 cp /tmp/test.txt s3://pg-percona-bkup
 We need to know the location of S3 bucket. If we don’t know, we can find out the bucket location, using the following command.

$ aws s3api get-bucket-location --bucket pg-percona-bkup
------- Sample output--------------
{
    "LocationConstraint": "us-east-2"
}
Refer to this amazon documentation to find out the endpoint for the S3 bucket of the region. 
Now, we can specify this configuration in pgBackRest configuration file. A sample configuration for S3 bucket in /etc/pgbackrest.conf is shown below.

[global]
repo1-path=/var/lib/pgbackrest
repo1-retention-full=5
repo1-s3-bucket=pg-percona-bkup
repo1-s3-endpoint=s3.us-east-2.amazonaws.com
repo1-s3-key=AKIxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxA
repo1-s3-key-secret=tKxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxX
repo1-s3-region=us-east-2
repo1-s3-verify-ssl=n
repo1-type=s3

[pg0app]
pg1-path=/var/lib/pgsql/11/data
pg1-port=5432

Once we have the required configuration in place, we can create the stanza and push the backup using the previously mentioned steps.

$ pgbackrest stanza-create --stanza=pg0app --log-level-console=info
$ pgbackrest backup --type=full --stanza=pg0app --log-level-console=info
The rest of the steps are the same as discussed earlier.



